00:01:06.700 --> 00:01:08.000
So, hello, everyone.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:09.300
I'm John Haidt.

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:11.680
I'm a professor at NYU Stern.

00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:14.370
And we'll be talking about,
in part about my book,

00:01:14.370 --> 00:01:16.370
The Coddling of the
American Mind.

00:01:16.370 --> 00:01:18.220
But a lot of my research
is, we'll be talking

00:01:18.220 --> 00:01:21.360
about some things that could
offend you or drive you crazy

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:23.130
if you're in that
normal reactive mode,

00:01:23.130 --> 00:01:24.430
but I hope this beautiful
setting,

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:27.540
this library, will put
us all in the mode like,

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:28.840
we've got problems,
let's think about them,

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:30.740
let's talk about them, and
that's what we're here to do.

00:01:30.740 --> 00:01:32.070
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Yeah, you know, John,

00:01:32.070 --> 00:01:34.310
mentioned that he got
his bachelor's degree,

00:01:34.310 --> 00:01:37.930
it was in philosophy at Yale,
a Ph.D. It was in psychology

00:01:37.930 --> 00:01:40.450
at the University
of Pennsylvania.

00:01:40.450 --> 00:01:43.930
And he went on to teach for 16
years at UVA before he ended

00:01:43.930 --> 00:01:46.980
up at the Stern School
of Business and the chair

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:49.530
for ethical leadership at NYU.

00:01:49.530 --> 00:01:54.610
I want to particularly emphasize
an earlier book he wrote,

00:01:54.610 --> 00:01:56.330
because we're going to
build a question on that.

00:01:56.330 --> 00:01:58.240
The first question I
have is built on that.

00:01:58.240 --> 00:02:02.740
It's, I think I would say,
his most acclaimed book.

00:02:02.740 --> 00:02:04.450
That still remains to be seen.

00:02:04.450 --> 00:02:06.540
Let's see what happens with
the -- with the new book,

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:08.270
The Coddling of the
American Mind.

00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:09.640
But it was a New York
Times bestseller.

00:02:09.640 --> 00:02:12.590
It's called The Righteous Mind,
Why Good People Are Divided

00:02:12.590 --> 00:02:14.070
by Politics and Religion.

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:15.370
I think if you want

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:16.720
to understand our political
divisions, in my opinion,

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:19.240
it's the single book
you should read.

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:21.340
In that book he offers
an account of the origins

00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:24.350
of the human moral sense
and he shows how variations

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:27.760
in moral intuitions can help
explain the polarization

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:31.030
and what some might call
dysfunction of our politics.

00:02:31.030 --> 00:02:34.160
So, a good place to start,
particularly here in Washington

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:36.570
for this particular
audience, is with that book.

00:02:36.570 --> 00:02:39.400
Can you tell us about your
research related to the book

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:42.340
and how you got from
The Righteous Mind

00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:43.660
to the coddled mind?

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:44.960
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt:
Coddled mind, right.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:46.260
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: And the
new book is The Coddling

00:02:46.260 --> 00:02:47.560
of the American Mind.

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:48.860
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Sure.

00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:50.160
So, I study morality.

00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:51.610
That's what I've done
since graduate school,

00:02:51.610 --> 00:02:53.960
and I look at it both from
an evolutionary perspective

00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:56.310
and cultural psychological,
or anthropological,

00:02:56.310 --> 00:02:58.330
perspective at the same time.

00:02:58.330 --> 00:03:02.180
And I was looking at how
cultures vary around the world

00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:04.320
and why there are a lot of
similarities and differences.

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:06.240
And in the 1990's
I began to notice

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:09.380
that the American culture was
heating up to such an extent

00:03:09.380 --> 00:03:11.980
that left and right were
like different countries,

00:03:11.980 --> 00:03:13.500
like different cultures.

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:15.700
We have different
American history.

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:17.230
If you ask, what's
American history on the left

00:03:17.230 --> 00:03:19.170
and the right, it's like
different countries.

00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:20.690
If you ask, what's
the U.S. Constitution,

00:03:20.690 --> 00:03:22.180
two different Constitutions.

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:24.310
You ask about climate science,
if you ask about so many things,

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:25.760
we're coming apart --
we were coming apart,

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:29.160
and that was in the 90's.

00:03:29.160 --> 00:03:31.540
So, I began studying about, and
originally I was on the left.

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:33.350
I was always on the
left when I was younger,

00:03:33.350 --> 00:03:37.240
and I began really studying
political psychology in order

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:39.420
to help the Democrats
win, because after 2000

00:03:39.420 --> 00:03:42.910
and 2004 I thought, they have no
clue how to talk about morality.

00:03:42.910 --> 00:03:45.460
I'd like to help them connect
with American morality.

00:03:45.460 --> 00:03:48.880
So, I set out to understand the
conservatives read conservative

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:51.000
writings and watch
conservative TV shows,

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:52.950
and what I discovered was

00:03:52.950 --> 00:03:55.610
that on any complicated issue
you want to think about,

00:03:55.610 --> 00:03:57.170
if you're not -- if
you're only looking

00:03:57.170 --> 00:03:59.110
at one perspective you can't
possibly understand it.

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:02.660
And I found it was so much
fun and so interesting to look

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:04.350
at things from a
conservative perspective

00:04:04.350 --> 00:04:06.390
and libertarian perspective.

00:04:06.390 --> 00:04:08.530
And so, eventually, I just sort
of stepped out and I said, okay,

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:10.220
I'm not on any team anymore.

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:12.340
And I think to be a social
scientist it's very helpful

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:13.640
to not be on a team.

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:15.620
It's really corrupting
to be on a team

00:04:15.620 --> 00:04:18.680
and to want certain results
to come out of your research.

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:21.550
So, I was working on the problem

00:04:21.550 --> 00:04:23.140
of political polarization
for a long time.

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:24.440
I wrote the book
The Righteous Mind.

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:26.200
It came out in 2012 and then
things kept getting worse

00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:27.830
and worse.

00:04:27.830 --> 00:04:30.370
But the basic perspective
that we are tribal creatures,

00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:34.020
we evolved for tribal conflict,
we're very good at doing us

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:36.220
versus them, and
this is the nature --

00:04:36.220 --> 00:04:38.000
this allows us to do sports.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.550
This allows us to do politics.

00:04:39.550 --> 00:04:41.590
It's all the same psychology.

00:04:41.590 --> 00:04:43.220
So, while I'm working
on this problem,

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:45.240
suddenly these strange
things start happening

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:48.130
in my backyard, namely
universities.

00:04:48.130 --> 00:04:51.680
Beginning in 2014 we started
seeing students asking

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:54.750
for trigger warnings, protesting
speakers on the grounds

00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:57.480
that if this speaker comes to
campus it will be traumatizing

00:04:57.480 --> 00:04:59.670
or damaging to some students.

00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:00.970
You know, you might say, well,

00:05:00.970 --> 00:05:02.270
why don't you just say
not go to the talk?

00:05:02.270 --> 00:05:03.570
But, no. They would say, no, no,

00:05:03.570 --> 00:05:06.130
we can't have this person
step foot on our campus.

00:05:06.130 --> 00:05:07.990
So, it was a new
morality, a new fearfulness

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:09.600
about words and ideas.

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:11.990
So, Greg Lukianoff
and I wrote this book.

00:05:11.990 --> 00:05:14.330
Greg Lukianoff came to me, he's
the president of the Foundation

00:05:14.330 --> 00:05:16.740
for Individual Rights in
Education, he came to me

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:20.650
with this idea that somehow
students were learning

00:05:20.650 --> 00:05:22.230
to interpret words and books

00:05:22.230 --> 00:05:26.150
and ideas using the exact
same cognitive distortions

00:05:26.150 --> 00:05:28.220
that he had learned not to do

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:30.880
when he learned cognitive
behavioral therapy.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:34.200
He had a suicidal
depression in 2007.

00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:36.870
He thinks cognitive
therapy saved his life.

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:39.380
You learn all these distortions,
black-and-white thinking,

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:42.680
catastrophizing, mind-reading,
labeling, all these things

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:44.560
that people sometimes
do, but depressed

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:46.910
and anxious people
do constantly.

00:05:46.910 --> 00:05:48.210
And, so, the therapist,
you stop --

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:49.510
you learn how to
stop doing that.

00:05:49.510 --> 00:05:51.910
And Greg noticed students
are beginning to really do

00:05:51.910 --> 00:05:54.720
that a lot, catastrophizing,
everything is good or evil.

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.470
Around 2014 we wrote an
article in The Atlantic,

00:05:57.470 --> 00:05:59.880
it comes out in 2015,
and we think we're done,

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:03.080
we did our analysis
of these trends.

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:05.570
And then, at Halloween of
2015, some of you know,

00:06:05.570 --> 00:06:08.240
some of you don't, but at
Halloween of 2015 at Yale,

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:10.520
and then it went everywhere,
it went many other places,

00:06:10.520 --> 00:06:12.070
there were giant protests.

00:06:12.070 --> 00:06:14.900
It like a new moral culture
had emerged on some campuses,

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:16.850
and it's a real puzzle, and
it's a very difficult one

00:06:16.850 --> 00:06:21.300
to work with, as we'll to,
but it's a callout culture.

00:06:21.300 --> 00:06:23.500
It makes it very difficult
for people to work together.

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:25.410
So, that's how we
got from my work

00:06:25.410 --> 00:06:27.810
on originally cultural
differences

00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:30.380
to political differences
and the culture war

00:06:30.380 --> 00:06:32.210
to what's going on campus.

00:06:32.210 --> 00:06:34.860
And I think during our
discussion we'll come then off

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:36.290
of campus back to politics.

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:39.600
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Yeah, we'll get
-- but sticking with campus is,

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:43.120
go into more detail about what
you identify as the issues

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:46.980
on campus and, in particular,

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:49.630
maybe a couple of
specific examples.

00:06:49.630 --> 00:06:52.640
I mean, some of them have gotten
a lot of press nationally.

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:55.450
You know, when I was
reading your book I noticed

00:06:55.450 --> 00:06:57.720
that you also brought in
examples that I hadn't heard

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:00.960
of before that were --
that were illuminating.

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:02.260
So, I'll --

00:07:02.260 --> 00:07:03.560
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Sure,
so, let me first check.

00:07:03.560 --> 00:07:06.770
How many of you, if I just
ask you about the protests

00:07:06.770 --> 00:07:09.710
at Berkeley when Milo
Yiannopoulos was scheduled

00:07:09.710 --> 00:07:11.010
to speak?

00:07:11.010 --> 00:07:12.310
Raise your hand if
you know what that is,

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:13.610
if you heard about that?

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:15.900
Okay, most, but not all of
you, the great majority of you.

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:17.200
Or, the protests at Yale

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:19.700
when Nicholas Christakis
was surrounded by students

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:21.680
who demanded he apologize,
raise your hand

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:23.510
if you know what that is?

00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:24.990
Okay, there's less than half.

00:07:24.990 --> 00:07:26.480
All right, so there are these --

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:30.950
the most spectacular events are
mobbing where students circle

00:07:30.950 --> 00:07:34.170
around a professor, a speaker,
and they demand that he be fired

00:07:34.170 --> 00:07:36.240
or he retract something.

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:37.540
Speaker shutdowns

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:39.710
where typically a conservative
speaker is invited to campus

00:07:39.710 --> 00:07:42.130
and the students demand
that he be disinvited.

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:44.130
And if the president

00:07:44.130 --> 00:07:46.350
of the university
won't disinvited them,

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:47.790
then they protest.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:49.810
They try to block people
from coming in, or they go

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:51.500
and they try to shout him down.

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:52.800
So, these things happen.

00:07:52.800 --> 00:07:54.310
There were some of
these in the 60's,

00:07:54.310 --> 00:07:56.930
but that didn't happen
for a long time.

00:07:56.930 --> 00:07:58.310
And then there's a lot now.

00:07:58.310 --> 00:07:59.800
By a lot I mean a few dozen.

00:07:59.800 --> 00:08:01.210
It's not happening
at every school,

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:02.790
but there are dozens of these.

00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:04.090
These are always videotaped.

00:08:04.090 --> 00:08:05.500
Everybody pulls out
their cellphone and, so,

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:06.800
they're on the Internet,

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:08.630
and especially right-wing
media sites love them

00:08:08.630 --> 00:08:11.280
because they really show
students being intolerant

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:13.800
of conservative ideas
and speakers.

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:15.320
Those are the most
spectacular things,

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:17.100
but those are fairly rare.

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:18.670
What I'd rather talk
about with you,

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:21.890
or what you may not know about,
is the really subtle ways

00:08:21.890 --> 00:08:24.590
that the speech climate
on campus has changed,

00:08:24.590 --> 00:08:26.950
and this is very
widespread and very damaging.

00:08:26.950 --> 00:08:28.540
So, I'll just share with
you a couple of examples,

00:08:28.540 --> 00:08:30.110
because now people --
you know, people write

00:08:30.110 --> 00:08:31.570
to me all the time now
with these examples.

00:08:31.570 --> 00:08:36.510
And so one -- so, I co-run a
group called Heterodox Academy,

00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:39.360
and the woman who now
runs it was a professor

00:08:39.360 --> 00:08:40.660
at Harvey Mudd College,

00:08:40.660 --> 00:08:42.670
at one of the Claremont
colleges in California.

00:08:42.670 --> 00:08:47.060
And she uses the example of how
a student came to talk to her --

00:08:47.060 --> 00:08:51.220
well, a student came to talk
to her and he started to say,

00:08:51.220 --> 00:08:53.940
you know, yeah, that's
a great idea,

00:08:53.940 --> 00:08:56.280
because that would
kill two birds with,

00:08:56.280 --> 00:08:59.340
and he covered his mouth.

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:00.640
And she said, what?

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:01.940
Were you going to say,
two birds with one stone?

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:05.510
And he said, well, yes,
but that would be violent.

00:09:05.510 --> 00:09:06.810
And he was afraid,
because if you say --

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:08.110
like, he could be called out,

00:09:08.110 --> 00:09:10.780
like he could be
shamed for saying that.

00:09:10.780 --> 00:09:13.560
There's another story from
another college in California.

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:15.910
Three students, this was
e-mailed to me by a friend,

00:09:15.910 --> 00:09:19.190
her daughter and two other
people were walking on campus

00:09:19.190 --> 00:09:21.310
and her daughter said,
wow, I'm starving,

00:09:21.310 --> 00:09:24.750
and her friends called
her out on that.

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:27.090
That's insensitive,
because there are people

00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:28.390
who are really starting.

00:09:28.390 --> 00:09:31.620
So, those are just two
examples from college.

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:34.400
But this sort of thing is
happening all the time, that is,

00:09:34.400 --> 00:09:37.650
students get prestige by showing
that they are more sensitive

00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:40.030
to various victim groups
or marginalized groups.

00:09:40.030 --> 00:09:43.330
They get prestige by calling
out someone for insensitivity.

00:09:43.330 --> 00:09:44.850
Now, most students
are perfectly normal

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:46.290
and sane are not doing this,

00:09:46.290 --> 00:09:48.310
but in any group there
are some who are.

00:09:48.310 --> 00:09:50.240
And, so, if you can imagine
what it's like to be a student

00:09:50.240 --> 00:09:52.340
where you never know when you're
going to be publicly shamed.

00:09:52.340 --> 00:09:54.300
And, of course, someone
could not tell you

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:56.590
that you're being shamed,
they just go and they put it

00:09:56.590 --> 00:10:00.710
on social media, and now
your reputation is destroyed.

00:10:00.710 --> 00:10:02.820
This sort of thing happens
at universities all the time.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:04.680
Now, it's creeping out
into the workplace.

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:06.860
So, this is not just on campus.

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:10.320
So, a woman who runs an
organization on business ethics

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:12.720
that I -- that I
cofounded, she said a friend

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:14.720
of hers was just reported to HR.

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:17.060
Why? Because she was
on a conference call,

00:10:17.060 --> 00:10:19.220
and after the conference call
the person they were talking

00:10:19.220 --> 00:10:22.490
to had been speaking so quickly
she said, wow, that guy sounded

00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:25.180
like he was on Ritalin, and
a few days later she's called

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:28.240
into HR because that
was insensitive,

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:31.420
insensitive to people
who have ADHD.

00:10:31.420 --> 00:10:34.830
Now, again, you can -- you can
discuss whether we should talk

00:10:34.830 --> 00:10:38.810
about this, but this is the
pattern, is you report someone.

00:10:38.810 --> 00:10:40.890
You don't -- you don't tend
to resolve it directly.

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:42.190
You report someone.

00:10:42.190 --> 00:10:44.300
And, so, here's a review
of my book on Amazon.

00:10:44.300 --> 00:10:47.050
Quote, I couldn't
understand why my new, bright,

00:10:47.050 --> 00:10:48.960
young workers kept running to HR

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:53.140
for every little interpersonal
problem and why they refused

00:10:53.140 --> 00:10:54.880
to show up to meetings
with the person

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:57.830
who they thought offended them,
because it's very threatening.

00:10:57.830 --> 00:11:00.420
If someone tells a joke
and you're offended,

00:11:00.420 --> 00:11:02.620
and you report them to
HR for having told a joke

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:05.320
to someone else, not even to
you, just you overheard it,

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:09.810
you're offended, it
would very frightening

00:11:09.810 --> 00:11:11.910
and traumatizing
even, to have to be

00:11:11.910 --> 00:11:13.470
in a room with that person.

00:11:13.470 --> 00:11:14.890
So, you just want
to report it to HR,

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:17.430
have them punish the person,
and leave you out of it.

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:18.870
Now, imagine what it
would be like to work

00:11:18.870 --> 00:11:20.590
with people like this.

00:11:20.590 --> 00:11:23.750
Again, most students,
most students are fine,

00:11:23.750 --> 00:11:25.780
but some have adopted
this new morality.

00:11:25.780 --> 00:11:28.590
Let me make clear, this
is not the millennials.

00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:30.110
Millennials are okay.

00:11:30.110 --> 00:11:32.010
This is the generation
after millennials.

00:11:32.010 --> 00:11:35.540
You see this in students
born in 1995 and after.

00:11:35.540 --> 00:11:37.080
So, that's the phenomena
we're talking about.

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:38.380
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: You know,
and that one hits you

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:39.990
with a [inaudible], because you
