00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:32.140
So, maybe you can go
into some of the --

00:12:32.140 --> 00:12:33.440
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Sure.

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:36.880
So, here's the -- so, there
are only two places in history,

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:40.020
in modern history, where
there's a clear dividing line.

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:41.560
So, in 1946 is one.

00:12:41.560 --> 00:12:44.620
If you were born in 1946
your childhood was different

00:12:44.620 --> 00:12:47.980
than if you were born in 1943,
because there was a, you know,

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:49.280
everything changed
after the war.

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:54.220
And, strangely, if you were
born in 1995, or afterwards,

00:12:54.220 --> 00:12:58.040
your child is different than if
you were born in 1992 or before.

00:12:58.040 --> 00:13:02.160
And, so, and the clearest
evidence of that is contained

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:04.500
in the book iGen by Jean Twenge.

00:13:04.500 --> 00:13:05.890
She goes through all kinds

00:13:05.890 --> 00:13:07.510
of nationally representative
studies

00:13:07.510 --> 00:13:09.590
about behavior of adolescents.

00:13:09.590 --> 00:13:11.950
And what you find is that
beginning with kids born

00:13:11.950 --> 00:13:17.360
around 1994, five,
they go out a lot less.

00:13:17.360 --> 00:13:19.650
They don't -- they're much
less likely to drink alcohol,

00:13:19.650 --> 00:13:21.820
much less likely to go out
on dates, much less likely

00:13:21.820 --> 00:13:24.060
to have ever worked for money.

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:27.540
They are much more anxious,
much more depressed.

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:28.840
Their lives changed.

00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:30.140
Their childhood changed.

00:13:30.140 --> 00:13:33.690
Now, why? So, they were
hit with a number of things

00:13:33.690 --> 00:13:36.300
that are different from the
millennials, the most important

00:13:36.300 --> 00:13:40.060
of which is Facebook opens
up in 2006 to the world.

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:42.880
So, you can be a 13-year-old,
or an 11-year-old who lies,

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:44.330
you can be a 13-year-old in 2006

00:13:44.330 --> 00:13:47.300
and you can get Facebook,
but very few do.

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:53.270
In 2007 when these kids are 11
or 12, the iPhone comes out,

00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:55.120
and now you can have
Facebook and social media

00:13:55.120 --> 00:13:57.340
with you all the
time, but very few do.

00:13:57.340 --> 00:13:58.900
It's quite expensive.

00:13:58.900 --> 00:14:02.440
But, gradually, by that
2009, a lot of them do.

00:14:02.440 --> 00:14:06.310
So, there's huge adoption
of social media around 2009,

00:14:06.310 --> 00:14:10.100
2010 by adolescents
in the United States.

00:14:10.100 --> 00:14:13.300
And right at 2011,
2012 the anxiety

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:16.390
and depression rates start
going steadily upwards,

00:14:16.390 --> 00:14:18.120
especially for girls.

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:21.600
So, social media is thought
to be the main culprit

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:25.650
for why things got so
bad after 2011, 2012.

00:14:25.650 --> 00:14:28.420
If you were a millennial and
you got Facebook in college,

00:14:28.420 --> 00:14:30.750
your brain was already
mostly formed.

00:14:30.750 --> 00:14:33.540
But if you're 13 when you
get Facebook, Instagram,

00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:36.680
all those things, the nature
of social relationships is

00:14:36.680 --> 00:14:41.770
so different and so much social
comparison and fear of shame

00:14:41.770 --> 00:14:44.020
that your sociality
is different.

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:46.280
So, social media is thought
to be the main thing.

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:51.590
But the other big thing is
the change in whether you got

00:14:51.590 --> 00:14:54.340
to be independent
between ages eight and 12.

00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:55.990
This is turning -- I'm
just discovering this now,

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:57.620
and let me do [inaudible]
with you.

00:14:57.620 --> 00:14:59.030
So, most of you here are --

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:01.210
the great majority
of you are over 40.

00:15:01.210 --> 00:15:04.450
What I want to ask you
is, how old were you

00:15:04.450 --> 00:15:08.370
when you were allowed outside on
your own, meaning you could walk

00:15:08.370 --> 00:15:10.830
to a friend's house
three blocks away?

00:15:10.830 --> 00:15:13.080
You could go down to the corner
store and buy a candy bar,

00:15:13.080 --> 00:15:14.890
or go get some milk to
bring home for your --

00:15:14.890 --> 00:15:16.240
you know, for the family?

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:17.590
How old were?

00:15:17.590 --> 00:15:20.220
Was it first grade, second
grade, third grade, sixth grade?

00:15:20.220 --> 00:15:22.870
You know, how old were you
when you were allowed out?

00:15:22.870 --> 00:15:25.070
First grade is usually
about, you know, six.

00:15:25.070 --> 00:15:27.940
So, fifth grade is
like around age 10.

00:15:27.940 --> 00:15:29.530
Think of your number
and then I'm just going

00:15:29.530 --> 00:15:31.840
to have you call it out.

00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:34.810
Okay, those of you over 40,
just call out the numbers.

00:15:34.810 --> 00:15:36.110
What age?

00:15:36.110 --> 00:15:37.410
&gt;&gt; Seven.

00:15:37.410 --> 00:15:38.710
&gt;&gt; Eight.

00:15:38.710 --> 00:15:40.010
&gt;&gt; Seven.

00:15:40.010 --> 00:15:41.310
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Okay,
this is what I always find,

00:15:41.310 --> 00:15:42.610
it's six, seven, or eight.

00:15:42.610 --> 00:15:43.910
This is what it always was,

00:15:43.910 --> 00:15:45.400
and this is what it
is around the world.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:47.510
I've studied street
kids all over the world.

00:15:47.510 --> 00:15:49.200
Street kids start
age seven or eight.

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:51.200
A five-year-old cannot
live out on the street.

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:54.120
A bunch of eight-year-olds can
run from the cops, steal food,

00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:56.040
and sleep under a bridge, okay?

00:15:56.040 --> 00:15:58.760
And most of you did something
like that, like not that bad,

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:00.420
but, you know, you
had adventures, okay?

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:02.580
Now, is there anybody
here under 25?

00:16:02.580 --> 00:16:03.880
I don't think so.

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:05.180
Anybody under 25?

00:16:05.180 --> 00:16:06.480
Raise your hand.

00:16:06.480 --> 00:16:07.780
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: We got someone.

00:16:07.780 --> 00:16:09.140
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Okay, what
age were you allowed out?

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:11.190
[ Inaudible ]

00:16:11.190 --> 00:16:12.490
Okay. What?

00:16:12.490 --> 00:16:14.210
[ Inaudible ]

00:16:14.210 --> 00:16:16.770
Okay, what I find when I
speak at colleges, it's 12,

00:16:16.770 --> 00:16:19.420
13, 14, sometimes 15, 16.

00:16:19.420 --> 00:16:22.140
Last week I spoke at Case
Western and one woman said six.

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:23.440
And I said, really?

00:16:23.440 --> 00:16:24.740
Where did you grow up?

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:26.040
And she said, well, the
Philippines, but when we --

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:27.340
then we moved here
when I was nine

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:29.660
and then I wasn't allowed
out until I was 14.

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:32.090
So, we've done this
giant experiment

00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:34.510
where there's this period
between eight to 12,

00:16:34.510 --> 00:16:37.400
which is the great period
of cultural exploration,

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:39.660
this is the period that
children's stories are about.

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:41.960
How many children stories do
you know that are about an eight

00:16:41.960 --> 00:16:44.890
or nine-year-old kid, you
know, or siblings who go off

00:16:44.890 --> 00:16:46.570
on an adventure with
their parents?

00:16:46.570 --> 00:16:47.870
Like, I guess it happens.

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:49.280
There's like The Swiss
Family Robinson or something.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:51.150
But it's almost always
they leave the parents

00:16:51.150 --> 00:16:52.450
and they go off and
have adventures.

00:16:52.450 --> 00:16:53.960
They learn how to
be independent.

00:16:53.960 --> 00:16:57.840
And what we've done, and we did
this in the '90s, this is why,

00:16:57.840 --> 00:16:59.920
this is why you get
the bright line,

00:16:59.920 --> 00:17:02.180
everybody up until the '90s,
including the millennials,

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:04.660
got the chance to practice
independence before it was too

00:17:04.660 --> 00:17:06.080
late, before the window closed.

00:17:06.080 --> 00:17:08.320
Eight to 14 is a critical --

00:17:08.320 --> 00:17:11.650
13, critical period for cultural
learning and accent learning.

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:13.870
If you're exposed to a
foreign language first

00:17:13.870 --> 00:17:15.170
at age 14, it's too late.

00:17:15.170 --> 00:17:16.610
You will never speak
it like a native.

00:17:16.610 --> 00:17:17.910
So, what we've done is,

00:17:17.910 --> 00:17:19.390
we've systematically
taken this critical period

00:17:19.390 --> 00:17:21.430
for cultural learning,
independence learning,

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:24.940
and we said, no independence
for you until it's too late.

00:17:24.940 --> 00:17:26.450
We'll wait until
the window closes,

00:17:26.450 --> 00:17:28.490
we'll wait until the
learning period is over,

00:17:28.490 --> 00:17:30.290
and then we'll say,
now you can go out.

00:17:30.290 --> 00:17:31.590
And guess what?

00:17:31.590 --> 00:17:32.890
They don't go out.

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:34.560
They don't go out.

00:17:34.560 --> 00:17:37.550
They sit on their bed with their
devices and they communicate.

00:17:37.550 --> 00:17:38.890
So, they're still social,

00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:41.080
but it's in the safety
of their room.

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:42.380
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So, you've
got a concept in there

00:17:42.380 --> 00:17:44.280
that there was going
to be anti-fragility.

00:17:44.280 --> 00:17:45.580
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Right.

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:47.040
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: And
that ties to this, right?

00:17:47.040 --> 00:17:48.340
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Yeah.

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:49.640
So, this is such a
powerful concept.

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:50.940
Raise your hand if you know
what that is, anti-fragility?

00:17:50.940 --> 00:17:52.240
Do you know what that is?

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:53.540
Very few. So --

00:17:53.540 --> 00:17:54.840
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
One guy back there.

00:17:54.840 --> 00:17:56.140
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: So, it's a --

00:17:56.140 --> 00:17:57.440
it's a term coined
by Nassim Taleb,

00:17:57.440 --> 00:17:58.740
the guy who wrote
The Black Swan.

00:17:58.740 --> 00:18:00.040
It's a brilliant concept.

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:02.010
It's a clunky word, but he made
it up because there is no word

00:18:02.010 --> 00:18:03.800
in the English language
and we need it.

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:06.740
So, if you think about it,
like a wine glass is fragile

00:18:06.740 --> 00:18:09.850
and nothing good happens if you
drop a wineglass on the ground.

00:18:09.850 --> 00:18:11.150
It's fragile.

00:18:11.150 --> 00:18:13.150
And, so, we give our
kids plastic cups.

00:18:13.150 --> 00:18:15.720
Toddlers get plastic cups
because those are resilient.

00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:18.230
They don't break, but
they don't get better.

00:18:18.230 --> 00:18:21.040
There's nothing good -- it's
like, a glass doesn't get better

00:18:21.040 --> 00:18:22.340
if you drop it on the ground.

00:18:22.340 --> 00:18:24.540
And what Taleb wanted
was a concept for things

00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:26.520
that get better when you
drop them on the ground.

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:30.790
So, he was studying the banking
system and he predicted in 2006,

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:34.080
he said, this banking
system is such a mess

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:36.170
and it's never been tested.

00:18:36.170 --> 00:18:37.610
It's never been tested.

00:18:37.610 --> 00:18:39.870
Anything goes wrong, it's
going down, and he was right.

00:18:39.870 --> 00:18:41.630
And, so, he was trying
to say, well,

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:44.230
what we need is something
more like the immune system.

00:18:44.230 --> 00:18:46.180
The immune system
is anti-fragile.

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:48.340
If you keep your kids
safe from bacteria,

00:18:48.340 --> 00:18:49.780
what are you doing to them?

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:51.080
You're just -- you're just --

00:18:51.080 --> 00:18:53.170
you're depriving their immune
system of the chance to learn.

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:55.340
The immune system
is anti-fragile.

00:18:55.340 --> 00:18:58.470
The reason why peanut allergies
are going up in this country is

00:18:58.470 --> 00:19:00.720
because we've been
protecting kids from peanuts.

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:02.680
We don't give them
a chance to learn

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:03.980
that peanuts are not harmful,

00:19:03.980 --> 00:19:05.650
their immune system
doesn't learn.

00:19:05.650 --> 00:19:09.090
So, this is our point in the
book, children are anti-fragile.

00:19:09.090 --> 00:19:10.780
They have to be -- they have

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:13.390
to face teasing,
insults, exclusion.

00:19:13.390 --> 00:19:15.560
They have to go out and
get lost and get scared

00:19:15.560 --> 00:19:18.010
and ask someone for
directions home.

00:19:18.010 --> 00:19:19.970
My kids refuse to ask
someone for directions.

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:21.550
It's terrifying for them.

00:19:21.550 --> 00:19:23.070
You know, because they
haven't had to do it.

00:19:23.070 --> 00:19:24.490
We're trying to push them out.

00:19:24.490 --> 00:19:27.010
Anyway, my point is, you need
a lot of negative experiences

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:28.310
in order to become
an independently

00:19:28.310 --> 00:19:29.610
functioning person.

00:19:29.610 --> 00:19:30.910
And in the name of
protecting them,

00:19:30.910 --> 00:19:33.820
we have denied them the negative
experiences that they need.

00:19:33.820 --> 00:19:36.040
We don't let them have those
until they're 15 or 16.

