00:20:10.620 --> 00:20:11.920
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Yeah.

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:13.220
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Let's --

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:14.520
first, let me lay out
the six causal threats,

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:15.820
because -- let's lay out --

00:20:15.820 --> 00:20:17.120
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Okay.

00:20:17.120 --> 00:20:18.420
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Like
the multiple causes,

00:20:18.420 --> 00:20:19.720
and then we'll talk about
how to reverse some of those.

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:21.120
So, I'm a social
scientist, and that means

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:25.400
that I study social
problems and I just tend --

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:27.470
you know, we tend
-- everything --

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:29.820
there's never one
factor causation.

00:20:29.820 --> 00:20:31.120
Almost anything interesting,
there's going

00:20:31.120 --> 00:20:32.420
to be all these different
intersecting,

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:33.720
interacting factors.

00:20:33.720 --> 00:20:36.230
And, so, we had this very sudden
emergence of this new morality

00:20:36.230 --> 00:20:38.060
on campus in 2014, 2015.

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:40.520
It seemed to come
out of nowhere.

00:20:40.520 --> 00:20:43.540
And Greg and I in the book, we
trace it out, we say, actually,

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:45.300
there's six intersecting
threats.

00:20:45.300 --> 00:20:47.970
There's like six fuses all
came together and then they met

00:20:47.970 --> 00:20:50.880
around 2014, 2015,
things blew up.

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:53.930
So, I'll just briefly
run through them.

00:20:53.930 --> 00:20:58.090
Number one is the political
purification of the universities

00:20:58.090 --> 00:21:01.370
at a time of increasing
political polarization.

00:21:01.370 --> 00:21:05.010
So, professors have always
leaned left, but between 1995,

00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:08.390
when it was just about two or
three to one left right ratio

00:21:08.390 --> 00:21:11.210
on the faculty, to 2010,
by then it's about five

00:21:11.210 --> 00:21:12.900
or six to one left right.

00:21:12.900 --> 00:21:16.160
And the core areas,
English, history, philosophy,

00:21:16.160 --> 00:21:18.090
it's more like 20 or
30 to one left right.

00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:22.260
So, we have universities
shifting much further left

00:21:22.260 --> 00:21:25.330
at a time when the culture
war is heating up, so left

00:21:25.330 --> 00:21:28.320
and right really, really
hate each other more.

00:21:28.320 --> 00:21:32.300
So, if universities are now
more clearly on one side

00:21:32.300 --> 00:21:35.560
of the culture war, their
internal dynamics are going

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:37.870
to be much more about
fighting the culture war.

00:21:37.870 --> 00:21:39.880
So, we're not free to
just explore ideas.

00:21:39.880 --> 00:21:42.320
If a conservative speaker comes
to campus, it's not like, oh,

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:43.620
what does he have to say?

00:21:43.620 --> 00:21:44.920
I'm sure he's a schmuck.

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:46.220
It's, what?

00:21:46.220 --> 00:21:47.520
We can't give him a platform.

00:21:47.520 --> 00:21:51.360
So, the rise in polarization and
political purification is one

00:21:51.360 --> 00:21:52.660
of the big factors

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:53.960
of why universities
have kind of gone crazy.

00:21:53.960 --> 00:21:57.610
Not most, but the shout downs
are almost all in the northeast

00:21:57.610 --> 00:21:59.310
and the coastal strip
of the west coast.

00:21:59.310 --> 00:22:00.610
That's where the violence

00:22:00.610 --> 00:22:02.850
and the intimidation is
taking place on campus.

00:22:02.850 --> 00:22:05.260
So, the culture war
is a big part it.

00:22:05.260 --> 00:22:08.600
Number two, the rise in
rates of mental illness.

00:22:08.600 --> 00:22:10.930
And, again, this is, I
mentioned this a moment ago,

00:22:10.930 --> 00:22:13.660
the statistics are stunning.

00:22:13.660 --> 00:22:17.260
The self-report anxiety is
going up by a factor of two

00:22:17.260 --> 00:22:20.280
or three in adolescence.

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:21.810
It's not just self-report,
it's not just

00:22:21.810 --> 00:22:23.890
that they say they're depressed.

00:22:23.890 --> 00:22:27.200
Hospital admissions for
self-harm, for taking --

00:22:27.200 --> 00:22:30.170
drinking poison, or cutting
yourself with a sharp object,

00:22:30.170 --> 00:22:32.500
those show the exact same
pattern, way up for girls,

00:22:32.500 --> 00:22:36.050
not so much up for boys, but
way up for teenage girls.

00:22:36.050 --> 00:22:41.400
Suicide is up 25% for boys from
the first decade of this century

00:22:41.400 --> 00:22:45.610
to the last couple years, 25%
increase in the suicide rate

00:22:45.610 --> 00:22:48.040
for boys, which is huge.

00:22:48.040 --> 00:22:54.100
For girls it's 70%, seven zero
percent increase in suicide

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:55.720
for teenage American girls.

00:22:55.720 --> 00:22:59.680
The same thing is
happening in the UK.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:02.340
So, we have a real
crisis on campus.

00:23:02.340 --> 00:23:04.420
This is even before
they get to campus.

00:23:04.420 --> 00:23:06.130
But now we have all these
people with depression

00:23:06.130 --> 00:23:08.090
and anxiety coming to campus,

00:23:08.090 --> 00:23:10.440
and some of them say they
want trigger warnings.

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:11.740
They want safe spaces.

00:23:11.740 --> 00:23:13.040
They want protection.

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:15.170
And what university can
say, no, tough it out?

00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:18.260
You can't say that, because
then if she commits suicide,

00:23:18.260 --> 00:23:20.400
of course, you're
exposed to liability.

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:21.900
I mean, there's other
reasons, compassion,

00:23:21.900 --> 00:23:23.550
of course, is a major reason.

00:23:23.550 --> 00:23:25.530
But the administrators,
and this is another threat,

00:23:25.530 --> 00:23:27.820
the administrators become
increasingly focused

00:23:27.820 --> 00:23:31.450
on liability, not on education,
so they get defensive.

00:23:31.450 --> 00:23:34.430
And, so, we get all these
things coming together

00:23:34.430 --> 00:23:37.310
to change the speech culture
and the administration on campus

00:23:37.310 --> 00:23:40.020
so that it's not
about healthy debate,

00:23:40.020 --> 00:23:41.660
it's not about vigorous
argument,

00:23:41.660 --> 00:23:45.830
it's not about fearless inquiry,
it's about safety in danger.

00:23:45.830 --> 00:23:47.380
And what we're talking
about the safety danger is,

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:50.090
ideas, books, words.

00:23:50.090 --> 00:23:53.700
So, my kids get this in third
grade, it's all about safety

00:23:53.700 --> 00:23:56.840
and danger, not physical,
emotional,

00:23:56.840 --> 00:23:58.780
and this is a terrible
thing to teach kids,

00:23:58.780 --> 00:24:01.350
that negative emotions
mean you're in danger and;

00:24:01.350 --> 00:24:02.970
therefore, you need protection.

00:24:02.970 --> 00:24:05.550
So, there's all these
things coming together

00:24:05.550 --> 00:24:09.230
so that kids born after 1995
haven't been given the chance

00:24:09.230 --> 00:24:11.500
to practice maturity
and independence.

00:24:11.500 --> 00:24:13.810
We've been overprotecting
them, and that's why the title

00:24:13.810 --> 00:24:15.710
of the book is The Coddling
of the American Mind.

00:24:15.710 --> 00:24:17.170
Coddling means overprotection.

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:20.420
And the subtitle is,
How Good Intentions

00:24:20.420 --> 00:24:23.310
and Bad Ideas Are Setting
Up a Generation For Failure.

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:26.460
So, anyway, all those threads,
they're hard to reverse.

00:24:26.460 --> 00:24:27.760
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Okay.

00:24:27.760 --> 00:24:31.320
So, my thinking when I read
the book, of the remedies,

00:24:31.320 --> 00:24:34.840
which are all these, what makes
sense when you get people away

00:24:34.840 --> 00:24:38.070
from their iPhones, universities
need to have more diversity

00:24:38.070 --> 00:24:40.800
of viewpoints in the faculty,
let's say, but those are running

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:43.880
into what I describe as
category six headwinds.

00:24:43.880 --> 00:24:45.180
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Uh-huh, yeah.

00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:46.660
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: I mean, it's
going against the zeitgeist,

00:24:46.660 --> 00:24:48.310
or whatever, however
you want to describe it.

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:50.610
So, what are you -- what are
you trying to do about that?

00:24:50.610 --> 00:24:52.570
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Yeah, so,
it's true that if you look

00:24:52.570 --> 00:24:54.250
at the six trends
that we lay out,

00:24:54.250 --> 00:24:57.010
none of them are
easily reversible,

00:24:57.010 --> 00:24:58.310
especially the polarization.

00:24:58.310 --> 00:24:59.660
That, I think, is just
going to get worse

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:01.090
and worse in this country.

00:25:01.090 --> 00:25:05.860
But I'm actually optimistic
that we can -- if you break --

00:25:05.860 --> 00:25:07.770
let's break the problem down.

00:25:07.770 --> 00:25:09.630
We have to change what
we're doing to kids.

00:25:09.630 --> 00:25:13.140
We have to change the
way we're teaching kids,

00:25:13.140 --> 00:25:15.680
especially in high school
before they get to college.

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:18.280
And then we have to change what
we're doing in universities.

00:25:18.280 --> 00:25:20.390
I'm really optimistic that
we can change childhood

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:21.690
for this reason.

00:25:21.690 --> 00:25:24.490
Parents want what's -- well,
parents want what's best

00:25:24.490 --> 00:25:28.140
for their kids, but
that's not entirely true.

00:25:28.140 --> 00:25:30.650
Parents really, really want
their kids to be successful,

00:25:30.650 --> 00:25:32.390
and especially to get
into a top college.

00:25:32.390 --> 00:25:34.430
And if that means their
kids have to be unhappier,

00:25:34.430 --> 00:25:37.570
they're going to do it.

00:25:37.570 --> 00:25:40.130
But now that it's becoming
clear that if you want

00:25:40.130 --> 00:25:43.950
to prepare your kid for success
and to get into a good college,

00:25:43.950 --> 00:25:47.600
don't make them study
-- don't schedule --

00:25:47.600 --> 00:25:50.650
don't overschedule them, make
them study from the age of four

00:25:50.650 --> 00:25:55.090
through 16, that's setting them
up for weakness and frailty.

00:25:55.090 --> 00:25:57.550
Now, that it's clear
there's no evidence

00:25:57.550 --> 00:25:59.470
that starting academic
training at age four,

00:25:59.470 --> 00:26:01.240
five, or six does any good.

00:26:01.240 --> 00:26:03.880
In Scandinavia and Germany they
don't start until age seven,

00:26:03.880 --> 00:26:05.510
before then it's all about play.

00:26:05.510 --> 00:26:08.090
That's what kids are
supposed to do, is play.

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:09.390
So, now that it's clear

00:26:09.390 --> 00:26:10.690
that there's a mental
health catastrophe,

00:26:10.690 --> 00:26:12.680
especially for girls,
now that it's clear

00:26:12.680 --> 00:26:15.780
that early academic training at
ages four, five, six don't help

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:18.450
at all, now that
it's finally clear

00:26:18.450 --> 00:26:21.890
that play is actually
what the kids need to do,

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:26.250
now we're in a situation where
lots of parents want to do that

00:26:26.250 --> 00:26:27.830
but they don't know
how to start.

00:26:27.830 --> 00:26:30.870
So, when I read about all this a
few years ago, a wonderful book,

00:26:30.870 --> 00:26:34.280
Free Range Kids by Lenore
Skenazy, I tried to get my seven

00:26:34.280 --> 00:26:36.710
or eight-year-old son to go
outside and go to the store,

00:26:36.710 --> 00:26:39.730
he'd say, but people
look at me funny.

00:26:39.730 --> 00:26:41.650
There are no other
kids out there,

00:26:41.650 --> 00:26:42.950
and he's afraid of
getting busted.

00:26:42.950 --> 00:26:45.060
I gave him a little
license that said, you know,

00:26:45.060 --> 00:26:48.500
if you're thinking of arresting
me, please go read Huck Finn,

00:26:48.500 --> 00:26:50.270
and then, you know, and
then call my father.

00:26:50.270 --> 00:26:52.160
You know, I have
permission to be outside.

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:55.230
But he was shy about it.

00:26:55.230 --> 00:26:57.460
So, it's a social
coordination problem.

00:26:57.460 --> 00:27:01.410
So, but there are ways
to solve the problem.

00:27:01.410 --> 00:27:04.290
So, Utah is the first state,
the only state in the country

00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:06.910
that passed a free-range
parenting law.

00:27:06.910 --> 00:27:10.500
They specifically said last
March, they finally passed it,

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:13.100
you cannot be arrested for
letting your kids outside

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:16.650
to play, and that clear
statement means a lot more

00:27:16.650 --> 00:27:20.560
parents are willing to say,
okay, kids, go to the park.

00:27:20.560 --> 00:27:24.880
So, if every state,
whatever state you're in,

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:26.660
call your state reps, ask them

00:27:26.660 --> 00:27:28.520
to introduce a free-range
parenting bill.

00:27:28.520 --> 00:27:29.960
That's the first step.

00:27:29.960 --> 00:27:32.970
Second, if you have kids or
grandkids, there are ways

00:27:32.970 --> 00:27:35.560
to coordinate so that all the
kids in the neighborhood know,

00:27:35.560 --> 00:27:39.620
you meet at this playground, you
meet in this person's backyard.

00:27:39.620 --> 00:27:42.530
Kids have to have a lot
more unsupervised time.

00:27:42.530 --> 00:27:44.960
Unsupervised doesn't mean
nobody knows where they are,

00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:47.010
it means no adult is watching.

00:27:47.010 --> 00:27:49.390
No adult is going to step
in to resolve conflict.

00:27:49.390 --> 00:27:50.940
If someone gets badly
hurt they know, okay,

00:27:50.940 --> 00:27:52.240
we go to Mrs. Smith's house.

00:27:52.240 --> 00:27:53.540
She's right there.

00:27:53.540 --> 00:27:56.970
But kids have to have a lot
more time to work out conflicts.

00:27:56.970 --> 00:27:59.370
That's preparation
for democracy.

00:27:59.370 --> 00:28:03.110
When kids play in groups they
learn how to work things out,

00:28:03.110 --> 00:28:05.410
how to keep the game
going by being responsive

00:28:05.410 --> 00:28:06.710
to other people's needs.

00:28:06.710 --> 00:28:08.100
They learn compromise.

00:28:08.100 --> 00:28:11.750
They learn how to enforce rules
and make rules that are fair.

00:28:11.750 --> 00:28:13.540
So, I'm actually
really optimistic.

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:15.840
There's so much unhappiness
with par [phonetic] --

00:28:15.840 --> 00:28:19.340
among parents about the lack
of play, the overscheduling,

00:28:19.340 --> 00:28:22.680
the constantly being on
devices, but, you know,

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:25.300
but if you just tell your
kid, you can't be on a device,

00:28:25.300 --> 00:28:26.600
what are they going to do?

00:28:26.600 --> 00:28:27.900
No, there's no other
kids outside.

00:28:27.900 --> 00:28:29.200
So, we have to solve all
the problems together.

00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:32.430
So, I'm optimistic we're going
to make progress on that.

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:33.780
In high schools --

00:28:33.780 --> 00:28:35.080
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Why
is it worse for girls?

00:28:35.080 --> 00:28:36.380
Why is the mental health --

00:28:36.380 --> 00:28:37.680
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Yeah.

00:28:37.680 --> 00:28:38.980
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Situation worse for girls?

00:28:38.980 --> 00:28:40.280
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt:
So, we don't know,

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:41.580
but the leading thought is this.

00:28:41.580 --> 00:28:42.880
So, again, this is Jean
Twenge, T W E N G E,

00:28:42.880 --> 00:28:44.250
who wrote this book, iGen.

00:28:44.250 --> 00:28:46.550
So, think about it this way.

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:48.210
All kids love devices.

00:28:48.210 --> 00:28:49.510
Most of us, when we were kids,

00:28:49.510 --> 00:28:51.520
we couldn't take our
eyes off the TV screen.

00:28:51.520 --> 00:28:53.610
Our parents said it
would rot our brains.

00:28:53.610 --> 00:28:56.330
It turns out, TV isn't
that bad for you,

00:28:56.330 --> 00:28:59.730
but not playing outside
is bad for you.

00:28:59.730 --> 00:29:03.920
So, the TV itself wasn't so bad.

00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:05.520
Social media is really
different.

00:29:05.520 --> 00:29:08.530
If you give -- if you suddenly
let all kids, you know,

00:29:08.530 --> 00:29:11.760
by age eight, nine, 10,
have a device, what happens?

00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:13.060
What do the boys do?

00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:14.450
Just call it out, those
of you who have sons.

00:29:14.450 --> 00:29:17.160
What do your boys
do with devices?

00:29:17.160 --> 00:29:18.460
Videogames, that's right.

00:29:18.460 --> 00:29:19.760
They play videogames
all day long.

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:22.050
It turns out, videogames
aren't really bad for you.

00:29:22.050 --> 00:29:25.600
They take you away from outdoor
play, but they're often social.

00:29:25.600 --> 00:29:27.000
My son is playing, you
know, they're like --

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.380
they're like, you know,
they're a team trying

00:29:29.380 --> 00:29:30.680
to kill other teams.

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:33.130
That's actually pretty
good for you.

00:29:33.130 --> 00:29:35.220
What do girls do?

00:29:35.220 --> 00:29:39.270
Girls are taking selfies,

00:29:39.270 --> 00:29:41.780
that take a long,
long time to compose.

00:29:41.780 --> 00:29:44.320
They have filters to make
themselves look more beautiful.

00:29:44.320 --> 00:29:46.770
So, we're all aware that
models are not real,

00:29:46.770 --> 00:29:49.840
that girls are exposed to models
in magazines that aren't real.

00:29:49.840 --> 00:29:51.880
We've talked about this
for 20 or 30 years,

00:29:51.880 --> 00:29:53.800
that girls have unreasonable
beauty standards.

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:56.720
Now, suddenly, their
friends, the women --

00:29:56.720 --> 00:29:58.680
the girls around
them, are distorted

00:29:58.680 --> 00:30:01.070
to look more beautiful, to
the point where now girls

00:30:01.070 --> 00:30:04.560
and young women are
asking for plastic surgery

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:07.990
so that they can look more
like their Instagram photos.

00:30:07.990 --> 00:30:11.430
So, girls are doing a lot
more social comparison.

00:30:11.430 --> 00:30:13.600
Girls feel much more inadequate.

00:30:13.600 --> 00:30:17.510
And, especially, girls'
sociality is based on who's in,

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:20.330
who knows whose secrets,
who is being excluded.

00:30:20.330 --> 00:30:21.630
Girls are much more about that.

00:30:21.630 --> 00:30:23.930
Boys are more about dominance in
sports, hierarchy, and ability.

00:30:23.930 --> 00:30:25.230
They're more vertical.

00:30:25.230 --> 00:30:26.530
Girls are more horizontal.

00:30:26.530 --> 00:30:27.830
And Facebook, Instagram,

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:31.300
these things are incredibly
powerful ways to let girls know

00:30:31.300 --> 00:30:34.450
that they were not included
in this fun, fun event,

00:30:34.450 --> 00:30:37.270
which is distorted to look
really super fun, to the point

00:30:37.270 --> 00:30:40.910
where some college girls say,
I can't make it to that party.

00:30:40.910 --> 00:30:43.960
Can you take my phone, take
some photos, and I'll post it

00:30:43.960 --> 00:30:45.620
to make it look like
I was there?

00:30:45.620 --> 00:30:47.200
I mean, this is crazy stuff,

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:50.120
but you can imagine
how teenage girls,

00:30:50.120 --> 00:30:51.620
it really does a number on them.

00:30:51.620 --> 00:30:53.790
If you -- so, if you first
get this stuff when you're 18

00:30:53.790 --> 00:30:55.090
or 19, it's not so bad.

00:30:55.090 --> 00:30:57.950
But if you first got it when
you were 13, in other words,

00:30:57.950 --> 00:31:00.300
if you were born in 1995 or
after, and you get this stuff

00:31:00.300 --> 00:31:03.560
when you were 13, it's
really bad for girls.

00:31:03.560 --> 00:31:05.330
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So,
switching gears a little bit.

00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:08.510
Well, let's stick with
that actually for a second.

00:31:08.510 --> 00:31:10.730
What about the headwinds
in universities?

00:31:10.730 --> 00:31:14.500
You know, because colleges, some
folks probably in this room went

00:31:14.500 --> 00:31:18.010
to some of the more elite
places, they're more liberal.

00:31:18.010 --> 00:31:21.620
You know, there's -- tenure
has the effect of, well,

00:31:21.620 --> 00:31:24.310
I'm going to hire people
who think like I do.

00:31:24.310 --> 00:31:26.410
That's supposed to be academic
freedom or something, right?

00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:27.710
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Yeah,
yeah, that's right.

00:31:27.710 --> 00:31:29.100
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So,
there isn't the diversity,

00:31:29.100 --> 00:31:31.580
and then you have this group
mentality, the Durkheimian thing

00:31:31.580 --> 00:31:33.180
that you -- that you raised.

00:31:33.180 --> 00:31:35.370
So, how do you combat that?

00:31:35.370 --> 00:31:37.490
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Yeah,
so, at universities we have

00:31:37.490 --> 00:31:39.150
to make a lot of changes.

00:31:39.150 --> 00:31:43.190
One reason I'm optimistic
is that anybody

00:31:43.190 --> 00:31:46.030
who is a university president
or dean or administrator,

00:31:46.030 --> 00:31:48.320
it's always been a difficult
job, but in the last two

00:31:48.320 --> 00:31:49.890
or three years they all
say their job is becoming

00:31:49.890 --> 00:31:52.520
impossible, because if
there's any conflict

00:31:52.520 --> 00:31:54.800
between any two students,
one person tells a joke,

00:31:54.800 --> 00:31:56.950
one person makes a reference,
one person wears a piece

00:31:56.950 --> 00:31:58.470
of clothing they
bought vacation,

00:31:58.470 --> 00:31:59.770
that's cultural appropriation.

00:31:59.770 --> 00:32:01.070
That's insensitive.

00:32:01.070 --> 00:32:02.370
That's offensive.

00:32:02.370 --> 00:32:03.700
And these things can
blow up to the point

00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:05.260
where they can get
into the newspaper.

00:32:05.260 --> 00:32:07.740
They never know when there
will be a group protesting,

00:32:07.740 --> 00:32:09.040
demanding that they intervene,

00:32:09.040 --> 00:32:10.340
demanding that they
punish someone.

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:12.140
It's an impossible situation.

00:32:12.140 --> 00:32:13.780
So, university presidents
are finally ready

00:32:13.780 --> 00:32:17.080
to exert some leadership, if
they -- if they know what to do.

00:32:17.080 --> 00:32:18.380
The first two years were marked

00:32:18.380 --> 00:32:20.060
by an almost complete
absence of leadership.

00:32:20.060 --> 00:32:23.430
One reason is because
the complaints often come

00:32:23.430 --> 00:32:26.300
from either the black
students' group,

00:32:26.300 --> 00:32:29.230
the women students' group, the
LGBT group, and nobody wants

00:32:29.230 --> 00:32:31.000
to stand up against them
and appear insensitive.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:32.300
We're very progressive.

00:32:32.300 --> 00:32:35.060
We're very focused on diversity
and inclusion to the extent

00:32:35.060 --> 00:32:37.330
that a lot of these protests
are linked in some way

00:32:37.330 --> 00:32:41.170
to an identity issue, nobody
can stand up against that.

00:32:41.170 --> 00:32:44.460
One reason I'm optimistic
is that in the last year

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:48.300
so many people, so many
great people, are writing,

00:32:48.300 --> 00:32:50.990
these are people who are
not straight white males,

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:53.890
are writing to say the way
we're doing identity politics is

00:32:53.890 --> 00:32:56.640
really bad for everybody,
including my group.

00:32:56.640 --> 00:32:59.390
So, you know, black
scholars are not uniform.

00:32:59.390 --> 00:33:01.140
There's a lot of diversity
among them, and we're beginning

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:05.060
to see some, like John
McWhorter, a whole bunch,

00:33:05.060 --> 00:33:06.360
that are now saying, wait,

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:07.860
this kind of identity
[inaudible] is really bad

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:09.300
for black students.

00:33:09.300 --> 00:33:13.970
Amy Chua, a Chinese-American
scholar at Yale Law School,

00:33:13.970 --> 00:33:16.350
has this great book
on political tribes.

00:33:16.350 --> 00:33:20.060
Francis Fukuyama just came out
with a book called Identity.

00:33:20.060 --> 00:33:22.890
So, a lot of scholars, who
are not straight white males,

00:33:22.890 --> 00:33:27.350
are saying, this is nuts to
say let's all band together,

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:28.650
us versus the straight
white males,

00:33:28.650 --> 00:33:30.700
because they are the source of
the problem and let, you know --

00:33:30.700 --> 00:33:33.970
the us versus them thinking
that is now rising in prominence

00:33:33.970 --> 00:33:35.610
on campus, this is
a dead-end street.

00:33:35.610 --> 00:33:38.040
This is never going to lead
to a welcoming environment

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:39.450
where people feel welcome.

00:33:39.450 --> 00:33:41.730
It's going to lead
to constant conflict.

00:33:41.730 --> 00:33:44.990
In -- and here, we can come back
to the country at large now,

00:33:44.990 --> 00:33:49.880
a multiethnic secular
democracy is like a contraption

00:33:49.880 --> 00:33:52.140
that should never fly.

00:33:52.140 --> 00:33:55.750
Political organization for our
species is almost always based

00:33:55.750 --> 00:33:59.600
on ties of blood or soil.

00:33:59.600 --> 00:34:03.540
You get religions like Islam
that transcend it with God.

00:34:03.540 --> 00:34:05.810
So, either blood, soil, or God.

00:34:05.810 --> 00:34:08.030
Those are your options.

00:34:08.030 --> 00:34:09.330
America was an experiment.

00:34:09.330 --> 00:34:10.830
We talk about the
American experiment.

00:34:10.830 --> 00:34:12.130
It was an experiment.

00:34:12.130 --> 00:34:13.660
It probably shouldn't
have worked.

00:34:13.660 --> 00:34:15.420
But, and it almost didn't work,

00:34:15.420 --> 00:34:17.880
but if you get everything
lined up right it can work.

00:34:17.880 --> 00:34:21.240
Clearly, a secular liberal
in the true, you know,

00:34:21.240 --> 00:34:23.570
philosophical sense, a secular
liberal democracy can work,

00:34:23.570 --> 00:34:26.200
and they worked all over
Europe until recently.

00:34:26.200 --> 00:34:27.500
Now they're not working.

00:34:27.500 --> 00:34:29.310
What's going on?

00:34:29.310 --> 00:34:32.960
Issues of immigration,
identity, division,

00:34:32.960 --> 00:34:35.380
these blow things apart.

00:34:35.380 --> 00:34:38.170
America was brilliant
in the 20th century

00:34:38.170 --> 00:34:40.380
at forming an overarching
identity,

00:34:40.380 --> 00:34:41.990
saying we don't care
what your blood is,

00:34:41.990 --> 00:34:44.290
we don't care we came
from, if you believe

00:34:44.290 --> 00:34:47.350
in the American ideals,
you're in.

00:34:47.350 --> 00:34:53.070
America had a way of creating
a superordinate identity

00:34:53.070 --> 00:34:55.320
that was the envy of the world.

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:58.770
And now, many of us think
we're going down roads

00:34:58.770 --> 00:35:02.840
of certain forms of identity
politics that reverse that

00:35:02.840 --> 00:35:05.520
and that turn our
diversity into a weakness.

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:07.340
Diversity is not
automatically a strength.

00:35:07.340 --> 00:35:10.200
It can be, it can
also be a weakness,

00:35:10.200 --> 00:35:12.380
and I think we're
mismanaging at universities,

00:35:12.380 --> 00:35:14.210
they're mismanaging a lot
of European countries,

00:35:14.210 --> 00:35:17.220
and the results could
be really devastating.

