So, there was -- it was much
more intense in the '60s.

00:41:13.580 --> 00:41:16.110
Then there was another wave
in the late '80s, early '90s,

00:41:16.110 --> 00:41:17.640
that was actually
more faculty driven.

00:41:17.640 --> 00:41:20.120
That was about diversifying
the cannon, the reading list.

00:41:20.120 --> 00:41:22.120
That sort of comes
out of humanities,

00:41:22.120 --> 00:41:24.690
protests against they had
too many dead white males

00:41:24.690 --> 00:41:26.100
on the syllabus.

00:41:26.100 --> 00:41:28.850
So, and then there's the new
one which started in 2014, 2015.

00:41:28.850 --> 00:41:30.150
So, you're right,
there's three waves.

00:41:30.150 --> 00:41:31.450
This is not new.

00:41:31.450 --> 00:41:34.630
What is new is the
medicalization of it.

00:41:34.630 --> 00:41:36.520
In other words, in
the previous waves,

00:41:36.520 --> 00:41:38.440
people said this is unjust.

00:41:38.440 --> 00:41:39.970
This must change.

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:43.150
Nobody said, this
is making me sick.

00:41:43.150 --> 00:41:45.610
This is going to
damage my friends.

00:41:45.610 --> 00:41:46.910
We need protection from that.

00:41:46.910 --> 00:41:48.210
Nobody said that.

00:41:48.210 --> 00:41:49.510
That's what's new.

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:51.550
And, so, that's what
Greg first noticed,

00:41:51.550 --> 00:41:53.150
was it's the medicalization,

00:41:53.150 --> 00:41:54.860
it's the idea that
we are fragile.

00:41:54.860 --> 00:41:57.390
We are so fragile
that we need you,

00:41:57.390 --> 00:41:59.380
the administrators,
to protect us.

00:41:59.380 --> 00:42:03.660
In the '60s what was different
was, the students were radical,

00:42:03.660 --> 00:42:04.960
but first of all,

00:42:04.960 --> 00:42:06.260
the administration
was often actually

00:42:06.260 --> 00:42:07.560
politically conservative.

00:42:07.560 --> 00:42:09.600
So, it wasn't -- the
whole campus wasn't

00:42:09.600 --> 00:42:11.010
on one page politically.

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:14.180
So, the ideology -- there was an
ideological conflict on campus,

00:42:14.180 --> 00:42:15.480
now there's not much
of a conflict

00:42:15.480 --> 00:42:17.320
on campus, it's all on one side.

00:42:17.320 --> 00:42:19.230
And then there's
the medicalization

00:42:19.230 --> 00:42:21.550
and then there's
the social media,

00:42:21.550 --> 00:42:25.050
which allows any little thing
can blow up within hours

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:27.400
to become a campus-wide
disaster.

00:42:27.400 --> 00:42:28.840
So, those are the
three big differences

00:42:28.840 --> 00:42:30.880
that make this situation
much, much --

00:42:30.880 --> 00:42:32.630
well, I shouldn't say worse,
because the '60s was --

00:42:32.630 --> 00:42:34.080
there was, again,
a lot of violence,

00:42:34.080 --> 00:42:35.830
but makes its this
one different.

00:42:35.830 --> 00:42:38.210
And it's what makes
this one so --

00:42:38.210 --> 00:42:40.310
it's not like this,
but it has spread.

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:42.960
These issues are now
out in the workplace.

00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:45.230
Not all industries,
but any industry

00:42:45.230 --> 00:42:48.060
that hires creative talent
from the top universities.

00:42:48.060 --> 00:42:52.660
So, journalism, tech, media,
the arts, I hear from people

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:53.960
in those industries,

00:42:53.960 --> 00:42:57.060
their recent hires are
doing this stuff there, too.

00:42:57.060 --> 00:43:01.320
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Got
a gentleman over here.

00:43:01.320 --> 00:43:03.620
[ Inaudible ]

00:43:03.620 --> 00:43:07.190
Is it on?

00:43:07.190 --> 00:43:09.290
&gt;&gt; Okay, thanks.

00:43:09.290 --> 00:43:12.220
I'm wondering if you've
looked at parenting

00:43:12.220 --> 00:43:14.900
for the age group
you're describing with --

00:43:14.900 --> 00:43:16.930
for kids who have special needs?

00:43:16.930 --> 00:43:18.730
I'm just wondering
to what degree --

00:43:18.730 --> 00:43:24.310
[ Inaudible ]

00:43:24.310 --> 00:43:25.610
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So,

00:43:25.610 --> 00:43:26.990
you're connecting what John
is talking about to kids --

00:43:26.990 --> 00:43:28.300
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Kids
with special needs?

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:29.600
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
With special needs,

00:43:29.600 --> 00:43:30.900
with special needs children?

00:43:30.900 --> 00:43:32.200
[ Inaudible ]

00:43:32.200 --> 00:43:34.700
&gt;&gt; Just what the effects
are for those types of kids.

00:43:34.700 --> 00:43:36.000
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt:
Yeah, that's a --

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:37.310
that's a very good question.

00:43:37.310 --> 00:43:42.630
So, Greg, actually, I can say --
I asked him if I can say this.

00:43:42.630 --> 00:43:45.020
Greg Lukianoff, my
co-author, has dyslexia.

00:43:45.020 --> 00:43:46.740
Now, that's not exactly --

00:43:46.740 --> 00:43:49.550
that's not exactly special
needs, but what you --

00:43:49.550 --> 00:43:54.140
what you hear -- so, many
very, very successful people,

00:43:54.140 --> 00:43:57.700
most very successful people
had major setbacks, traumas,

00:43:57.700 --> 00:43:59.380
obstacles in childhood.

00:43:59.380 --> 00:44:02.770
So, depending on
how it's handled,

00:44:02.770 --> 00:44:06.120
those things could be the
thing that they overcome,

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:09.100
and that's part of the
anti-fragility principle.

00:44:09.100 --> 00:44:12.540
I don't know how special-needs
kids are treated now.

00:44:12.540 --> 00:44:13.840
I should. That's a great point.

00:44:13.840 --> 00:44:15.590
Because if our whole point is,

00:44:15.590 --> 00:44:19.020
since the '90s we've been
massively over protecting kids,

00:44:19.020 --> 00:44:20.970
presumably we're doing it even
more for special needs kids.

00:44:20.970 --> 00:44:23.770
So, it would be fascinating to
see whether special needs kids

00:44:23.770 --> 00:44:25.390
who grew up in the
'70s or '80s ended

00:44:25.390 --> 00:44:26.950
up being much more successful,

00:44:26.950 --> 00:44:29.040
but those '90s are
overprotected.

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:33.120
I recently came across a
concept, the dignity of risk,

00:44:33.120 --> 00:44:34.420
I think it was called.

00:44:34.420 --> 00:44:37.810
It comes at a disability
scholarship, where when you're

00:44:37.810 --> 00:44:40.410
in a protective role to a
person, say in a wheelchair,

00:44:40.410 --> 00:44:42.950
with a disability, and you
make the decision for them

00:44:42.950 --> 00:44:46.220
about what risks they can take,
you're infantilizing them,

00:44:46.220 --> 00:44:47.630
you're denying them dignity.

00:44:47.630 --> 00:44:50.410
And, so, some disability
rights activists say,

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:52.060
let us make our own choices.

00:44:52.060 --> 00:44:53.360
Let us take some risks.

00:44:53.360 --> 00:44:55.170
You can't make all
our decisions for us.

00:44:55.170 --> 00:44:56.470
I think it's an important
concept

00:44:56.470 --> 00:44:57.950
for child rearing in general.

00:44:57.950 --> 00:45:01.040
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: We have
another [inaudible] here.

00:45:01.040 --> 00:45:05.660
So, we'll have the lady here and
