00:45:05.660 --> 00:45:06.960
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:45:06.960 --> 00:45:10.030
You probably, I am going to
guess, are familiar with,

00:45:10.030 --> 00:45:12.480
and I'm not going to get
his first name at all,

00:45:12.480 --> 00:45:15.900
but I believe his last
name is Louv, L O U V,

00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:18.870
who wrote a book called
Last Child in The Woods.

00:45:18.870 --> 00:45:20.170
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Oh yeah.

00:45:20.170 --> 00:45:21.470
&gt;&gt; And about the way
that our relationship

00:45:21.470 --> 00:45:24.260
to the natural world
has changed completely,

00:45:24.260 --> 00:45:27.210
because children are not
encouraged to go out and play

00:45:27.210 --> 00:45:29.710
in nature, or close to nature,
probably not wilderness,

00:45:29.710 --> 00:45:32.920
and that the consequences
of that, it cuts us off

00:45:32.920 --> 00:45:36.680
from forming profound emotional
connections with the world

00:45:36.680 --> 00:45:40.070
in a way that we badly need if
we are going to do something

00:45:40.070 --> 00:45:41.380
about climate change,
among other things.

00:45:41.380 --> 00:45:42.680
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt:
Absolutely, yes.

00:45:42.680 --> 00:45:43.980
&gt;&gt; And it seems it dovetails

00:45:43.980 --> 00:45:45.280
with what you're talking
about very nicely.

00:45:45.280 --> 00:45:46.730
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt:
It absolutely does.

00:45:46.730 --> 00:45:49.410
An interesting thing about
the current phenomena

00:45:49.410 --> 00:45:51.820
that we're writing about is
that it's happening in all

00:45:51.820 --> 00:45:53.120
of the Anglosphere countries.

00:45:53.120 --> 00:45:55.770
It's not happening on
continental Europe.

00:45:55.770 --> 00:46:00.800
And one reason is that the
UK did what we did in saying,

00:46:00.800 --> 00:46:04.000
we've got to get kids learning
math earlier and earlier,

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:06.780
whereas in Germany,
Switzerland, Scandinavia,

00:46:06.780 --> 00:46:08.080
they send the kids out.

00:46:08.080 --> 00:46:09.500
I know they do this in
Switzerland and Germany,

00:46:09.500 --> 00:46:12.950
at four the kids are -- one of
the main activities is, okay,

00:46:12.950 --> 00:46:14.390
we're going out into the woods,

00:46:14.390 --> 00:46:16.530
and they might even
have a hatchet or a saw.

00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:19.390
Let's make a fire, you
know, with five-year-olds.

00:46:19.390 --> 00:46:21.910
And it may happen that
a kid gets burned.

00:46:21.910 --> 00:46:23.210
That might happen.

00:46:23.210 --> 00:46:24.510
And then guess what?

00:46:24.510 --> 00:46:25.810
They learn.

00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:27.110
They learn.

00:46:27.110 --> 00:46:28.410
So, there's this great
thing on Staten Island --

00:46:28.410 --> 00:46:31.110
Governors Island in New York
called the Junkyard Playground

00:46:31.110 --> 00:46:34.210
where I had to sign like a
huge several page release

00:46:34.210 --> 00:46:38.410
to let my kids in, but there's
hammers and nails and lumber

00:46:38.410 --> 00:46:39.710
and kids could get hurt.

00:46:39.710 --> 00:46:42.440
And I watched, and
they sometimes do.

00:46:42.440 --> 00:46:45.740
Like I watched a kid pounding
a nail and he hit his thumb,

00:46:45.740 --> 00:46:47.180
and he didn't go
running off crying.

00:46:47.180 --> 00:46:49.890
Just went like this, owe, and
he picked up the nail again

00:46:49.890 --> 00:46:51.230
and he kept going
and did it again.

00:46:51.230 --> 00:46:53.590
And by the third
time, he learned how

00:46:53.590 --> 00:46:55.090
to -- how to pound a nail.

00:46:55.090 --> 00:46:57.520
So, kids get experience
in nature.

00:46:57.520 --> 00:46:59.390
Kids always have.

00:46:59.390 --> 00:47:04.300
Because we got this crazy
idea in our heads in the '80s

00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:07.700
that if the kid is unsupervised,
if no adult is watching,

00:47:07.700 --> 00:47:10.390
that kid will be abducted
by a sexual predator.

00:47:10.390 --> 00:47:12.930
That kid will be -- or,
that kid will be abducted.

00:47:12.930 --> 00:47:14.690
We got this idea
because of cable TV.

00:47:14.690 --> 00:47:16.190
We freaked out in the '80s.

00:47:16.190 --> 00:47:18.060
By the '90s we stopped
letting kids out.

00:47:18.060 --> 00:47:20.280
And the two most
dangerous places

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:22.420
that we would never let our
kids go are public restrooms

00:47:22.420 --> 00:47:23.720
and the woods.

00:47:23.720 --> 00:47:25.020
We would never let our kids
go to those two places,

00:47:25.020 --> 00:47:26.590
because who knows what
will happen to them there,

00:47:26.590 --> 00:47:29.460
and it's a real shame for
exactly the reasons you say.

00:47:29.460 --> 00:47:31.700
And, so, this is one of things
I'm hopeful about, that,

00:47:31.700 --> 00:47:35.550
you know, so many people are
recognizing like nature is good.

00:47:35.550 --> 00:47:36.850
We have to let kids out into it.

00:47:36.850 --> 00:47:38.500
And, so, I think if we can --

00:47:38.500 --> 00:47:40.400
it's scary to let
your kid out alone,

00:47:40.400 --> 00:47:42.210
but if schools start
letting them out,

00:47:42.210 --> 00:47:45.050
if parents get together and
make an effort, I think --

00:47:45.050 --> 00:47:46.760
I think we can reclaim
the woods.

00:47:46.760 --> 00:47:49.570
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
This fellow here.

00:47:51.890 --> 00:47:54.470
&gt;&gt; Do you have any thoughts
on, what if colleges went

00:47:54.470 --> 00:47:57.700
to a more open admissions
sort of arrangements,

00:47:57.700 --> 00:48:00.570
what might that do to, for
example, high school kids

00:48:00.570 --> 00:48:05.580
who now are under such pressure,
they might be able to, you know,

00:48:05.580 --> 00:48:08.360
enjoy life a little bit more
and not have such pressure

00:48:08.360 --> 00:48:10.390
when they're in high school,
and then when they get

00:48:10.390 --> 00:48:14.370
to get college maybe you'd have
a more diverse, more inclusive,

00:48:14.370 --> 00:48:18.280
more -- less inequality?

00:48:18.280 --> 00:48:21.060
&gt;&gt; Jonathan Haidt: Yeah, so,
in America I think it would --

00:48:21.060 --> 00:48:24.270
we'd never go to a totally
open admissions policy.

00:48:24.270 --> 00:48:27.030
We do -- we are committed
in some ways to some kinds

00:48:27.030 --> 00:48:30.720
of meritocracy, but our
meritocracy has gotten too much

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:33.070
test based, and that
is a problem.

00:48:33.070 --> 00:48:35.110
We reward people for
the kind of intelligence

00:48:35.110 --> 00:48:36.510
that does well on tests.

00:48:36.510 --> 00:48:38.640
And then there's a wonderful
column by Ivan Krastev,

00:48:38.640 --> 00:48:39.940
who's actually a fellow here

00:48:39.940 --> 00:48:41.680
in the New York Times
two years ago,

00:48:41.680 --> 00:48:45.960
about how the really twisted
thing about our meritocracy is

00:48:45.960 --> 00:48:47.750
that we reward people for
doing well on the test,

00:48:47.750 --> 00:48:49.390
and then they believe
they deserved it

00:48:49.390 --> 00:48:51.030
because they did
well on the test.

00:48:51.030 --> 00:48:52.330
So, there are problems.

00:48:52.330 --> 00:48:55.010
And there are some
interesting proposals to say

00:48:55.010 --> 00:48:57.860
above a certain level of
grades and test scores,

00:48:57.860 --> 00:49:00.300
above that we do it randomly.

00:49:00.300 --> 00:49:01.600
Those would be hard
to implement,

00:49:01.600 --> 00:49:03.280
but those might do some good.

00:49:03.280 --> 00:49:04.660
I would rather we
go another way.

00:49:04.660 --> 00:49:06.190
The problem you're
trying to address is

00:49:06.190 --> 00:49:09.650
that kids are pressured so
much to succeed, middle-class,

00:49:09.650 --> 00:49:11.490
upper-middle-class kids
[inaudible] so much pressure,

00:49:11.490 --> 00:49:13.450
there's no time for play.

00:49:13.450 --> 00:49:16.990
What we suggest in the
book is that we should --

00:49:16.990 --> 00:49:18.290
we should accept the fact

00:49:18.290 --> 00:49:21.030
that 18-year-olds should
not be on college campuses.

00:49:21.030 --> 00:49:23.210
Eighteen-year-olds today,
as Jean Twenge puts it,

00:49:23.210 --> 00:49:25.650
showing the data, an 18-year-old
today is about the same

00:49:25.650 --> 00:49:28.000
as a 15-year-old
from 30 years ago.

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:30.390
Eighteen-year-olds, American
18-year-olds are generally --

00:49:30.390 --> 00:49:32.010
some of them are
certainly ready,

00:49:32.010 --> 00:49:35.200
but a lot of them are just not
ready to be on a college campus.

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:37.870
And when we bring them to
college campuses, they end up --

00:49:37.870 --> 00:49:42.130
many of them end up requesting
infantilizing procedures,

00:49:42.130 --> 00:49:45.410
which then damages everything
else for everyone else.

00:49:45.410 --> 00:49:50.680
What if the top schools all
say, we strongly favor people

00:49:50.680 --> 00:49:53.880
who have taken a year or
two off, had a gap year,

00:49:53.880 --> 00:49:56.570
done military service, lived
somewhere else in the country.

00:49:56.570 --> 00:49:59.420
We think a red, blue switch,
like if you're from a blue area,

00:49:59.420 --> 00:50:02.080
go get a job in a red area,
or vice versa, meet people.

00:50:02.080 --> 00:50:05.060
We've got to get kids
away from their parents.

00:50:05.060 --> 00:50:07.320
Now, boarding school
might seem like a way,

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:08.660
and I need to do
research on this,

00:50:08.660 --> 00:50:10.530
boarding school also
infantilizes

00:50:10.530 --> 00:50:12.130
and teaches some bad
habit, some of them.

00:50:12.130 --> 00:50:14.710
I don't know enough to
comment on all of them.

00:50:14.710 --> 00:50:18.020
But if colleges, if Harvard
and Yale start saying,

00:50:18.020 --> 00:50:19.630
we're not going to
get the, you know,

00:50:19.630 --> 00:50:21.960
the person who did 12
extracurriculars in addition

00:50:21.960 --> 00:50:24.180
to double 800's on the
SAT, we're not going

00:50:24.180 --> 00:50:25.480
for that person anymore.

00:50:25.480 --> 00:50:28.440
We're going to favor military
veterans, people who went off

00:50:28.440 --> 00:50:30.540
and did something for a
couple years, and we're going

00:50:30.540 --> 00:50:32.670
to favor people who
are 19 or 20 years old.

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:34.050
That would be a better
way, I think,

00:50:34.050 --> 00:50:35.590
to take the pressure off kids,

00:50:35.590 --> 00:50:40.900
to make parents stop pressuring
their kids to achieve, achieve,

00:50:40.900 --> 00:50:43.190
achieve for your resume.

00:50:43.190 --> 00:50:44.890
&gt;&gt; So, we're going to wrap
up the conversation there.

